  <static seed="1441" source="Contrib/PCC/Math95/ComplexFractions/ComplexFractions6.pg">
    <statement><p>Simplify this expression, and if applicable, write the restricted domain.</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{\frac{{3+\frac{1}{t-6}}}{{\frac{1}{t-6}-\frac{1}{9}}}=}</m> <fillin characters="40" name="AnSwEr0001"/></p>
</statement>
    <answer>
      <p>
        <m>\frac{9\mathopen{}\left(3t-17\right)}{-t+15}, t\ne 6</m>
      </p>
    </answer>
    <solution><p>To simply the complex fraction <m>\frac{{3+\frac{1}{t-6}}}{{\frac{1}{t-6}-\frac{1}{9}}}</m>, we multiple the numerator and denominator with the common denominator of <m>{3+\frac{1}{t-6}}</m> and <m>{\frac{1}{t-6}-\frac{1}{9}}</m>, which is <m>{9\mathopen{}\left(t-6\right)}</m>.</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{\begin{aligned}
  \frac{{3+\frac{1}{t-6}}}{{\frac{1}{t-6}-\frac{1}{9}}} \amp = \frac{({3+\frac{1}{t-6}})\cdot{9\mathopen{}\left(t-6\right)}}{({\frac{1}{t-6}-\frac{1}{9}})\cdot{9\mathopen{}\left(t-6\right)}} \\
    \amp = \frac{{3\cdot 9\mathopen{}\left(t-6\right)+\frac{1}{t-6}\cdot 9\mathopen{}\left(t-6\right)}}{{\frac{1}{t-6}\cdot 9\mathopen{}\left(t-6\right)-\frac{1}{9}\cdot 9\mathopen{}\left(t-6\right)}} \\
    \amp = \frac{{27\mathopen{}\left(t-6\right)+9}}{{9-\left(t-6\right)}} , t\ne6 \\
    \amp = \frac{{27t-162+9}}{{9-t+6}}, t\ne6  \\
    \amp = \frac{{27t-153}}{{15-t}}, t\ne6 \\
    \amp = {\frac{9\mathopen{}\left(3t-17\right)}{-t+15}, t\ne 6}
\end{aligned}
    }</m></p>
<p>Since the factors <m>t-6</m> was canceled, the domain condition lost during the simplification is <m>t \ne 6</m>.</p>
</solution>
